rewster (1567–1644) was the son of the bailiff of the manor of Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, home of one of the earliest Puritan congregations. He was a prominent leader in Plymouth Colony from the 1620s until his death."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewere</i> ‘brewer’ (an agent derivative of Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). Compare   Brewster  .","English (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Bruyère</b> (see   Bruyere  ), a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heath’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Dutch   Brouwer  , German   Brauer   or   Breuer  , etc., all occupational names meaning ‘brewer’."]},{"name":"Bruster","meanings":["English: variant of   Brewster  .","Swiss German: variant of the topographic name   Brust   2, the suffix <i>-er</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Galfridus Brewster was born in 1380, in Rushmere, Suffolk, England as the son of Sir John Brewster III. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1410, in Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 30, and was buried in Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1380–1410":"1380–1410","1380–1440":"1380–1440","1325–1379":"1325–1379","1325":"1325","1379":"1379","1410":"1410","1440":"1440","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","